body:
$! If you're owed money by someone in another EU country, you can recover the debt using internationally-recognised court forms. $!

This is known as making a 'cross-border' claim. You will have to pay a court fee.

##If they admit owing the money

If the other person or business admits owing the money, you can make a [European Order for Payment.](https://e-justice.europa.eu/content_european_payment_order-41-eu-en.do "European Payment Order"){:rel="external"}

##If they deny owing the money

If they deny owing the money, and you're owed less than €2,000, you can use the [European Small Claims procedure.](https://e-justice.europa.eu/content_small_claims-42-en.do "European Small Claims Procedure"){:rel="external"}

For larger sums of money, you may have to use the national court system, and should get legal advice:

- [find a legal adviser (England and Wales)](http://legaladviserfinder.justice.gov.uk/AdviserSearch.do "find a legal adviser"){:rel="external"}
- [find a solicitor (Scotland)](http://www.lawscot.org.uk/wcm/lssservices/find_a_solicitor/Core/directory.aspx "find a solicitor (Scotland)"){:rel="external"}

Find out more about [making a cross-border claim in the EU.](http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetLeaflet.do?court_leaflets_id=1048 "making a cross-border claim in the EU"){:rel="external"}
